        "8:30 AM — Roorkee. A pleasant town with the famous IIT Roorkee campus — India's oldest technical institute, founded 1847 as the Thomason College of Civil Engineering. Quick chai break.",
        "9:30 AM — Arrive Haridwar. The Ganga enters the plains here — the river is cold, fast, and green-blue, nothing like it looks in the plains further downstream. Park at the Har Ki Pauri parking lot (₹50 for cars) — the ghats are pedestrian-only from here.",
        "10:00 AM — Mansa Devi Temple (ropeway from Birla Ghat). The ropeway (₹90 return) climbs to 2,045 ft in 3 minutes. The temple is dedicated to Goddess Mansa (the serpent goddess). Tie a 'mannat' thread on the tree in the temple courtyard — tradition says wishes are granted here. Panoramic views of Haridwar and the Ganga valley from the top. Queue on weekends — arrive early.",
        "11:30 AM — Chandi Devi Temple (separate ropeway from Chandighat, ₹126 return). Second major hill temple, across the river from Mansa Devi. The idol here is said to have been installed by the Hindu hero Adi Shankaracharya in the 8th century.",
        "1:00 PM — Har Ki Pauri ghat. Walk the full length of the ghats — Har Ki Pauri is where the Ganga is most sacred (the footprint of Vishnu is marked here). Watch pilgrims bathing, priests performing puja, and the constant movement of saffron-clad sadhus. The bathing rituals happen all day but are most active in the early morning.",
        "1:30 PM — Lunch near the ghats. Mohan Ji Puri Wale (near Har Ki Pauri) for piping hot puri-sabzi — simple, vegetarian, and ₹80. Chotiwala Restaurant on the ghat road for sit-down thali (₹200–350). Haridwar is strictly vegetarian and no alcohol.",
        "2:30 PM — Market walk. Bara Bazaar and Moti Bazaar are full of puja items, brass idols, Rudraksha beads, Ayurvedic products, and temple garlands. The Gangajal (Ganga water) in sealed bottles is sold everywhere — ₹20–50 for small containers that pilgrims carry home.",
        "4:30 PM — Har Ki Pauri for the evening Ganga Aarti (begins at sunset — 6:00 PM in winter, 7:00 PM in summer). Arrive by 5:30 PM minimum. The steps fill completely. Seven priests perform the aarti simultaneously with large fire torches, incense, and conch shells. Hundreds of diyas are released on the river at the end — floating dots of fire disappearing into the current. This is one of the most powerful rituals in India.",
